prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: Continuum and spectral line mapping in Band 6 of 70 Hi-GAL clumps toward the l=224 field
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: Two spectral windows are used to cover the 13CO(2-1) and C18O(2-1) lines, and three non-overlapping 2GHz basebands in Band 6 are used for continuum.

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText: If it is possible (and safe) to set the 13CO and 12CO(2-1) lines at the edges of the basebands, we would like to observe also 12CO(2-1).

Given that it would be unfeasible to map large (>~0.1 sq.deg.) areas of the sky, we exploit the already identified clumps in the Hi-GAL survey to point and map them individually with ALMA+ACA. In order to measure the FMF (see Scientific Justification) we require an angular resolution ~3arcsec to detect and separate fragments down to a level of <~0.01pc (at a distance of 1kpc). Our simulations with the OST have shown that the best trade-off is achieved at a wavelength of ~1mm (Band 6). At longer wavelengths the dust continuum emission would be too low, whereas at shorter wavelengths the primary beam would be too small. The expected recoverable structure of about 18arcsec (<~0.1pc) is adequate for this project.

Model: In order to test different observational scenarios, we have preferred to use a simple model rather than a pre-existing image. We have theerefore built a simple model with three (spherical) dense cores (at a distance of 1kpc and with central temperatures 15 to 25K) surrounded by a colder shell and envelope. Both temperature and column density decreases radially and the core radii vary from 0.01 to 0.02pc, yielding total core masses of ~1 to 3 Msun. The expected column density distribution has been converted into flux density and a background emission has been added. The original model and the returned images by the OST are shown in Fig.2 of the "Scientific Justification". We note that the two warmer and more compact cores are clearly imaged by ALMA. The larger core is still marginally detected in the dust continuum, but has been filtered out in the ALMA C18O(2-1) map (and recovered in the ACA image).
Continuum sensitivity For the model considered here the continuum peak intensity vary from ~1 to 5mJy/beam. A continuum sensitivity of <~0.1 mJy/beam is thus adequate.
Spectral sensitivity: In band 6 we will be able to observe simultaneously the 13CO and C18O(2-1) lines. Our simulations show that with 10min integration time and 0.4 km/s channel width, the less abundant and less intense C18O(2-1) line is well detected toward the two most compact cores (see Fig.2). The more abundant 13CO and 12CO will be detectable in the low-mass cores even with less integration time. The spectral peak flux densities in the source list are pessimistic values and refer to the lowest mass cores and weaker C18O(2-1) line.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: Stars form in dense, dusty clumps and the observed similarity between their mass distribution and the IMF supports the idea that clumps may fragment into sub-structures ("cores" or fragments) which then form stars or even clusters of stars. However, the transition from the observed "clump mass function" (CMF) to the IMF is still poorly understood theoretically, and not well constrained observationally. We propose to map with ALMA+ACA the structure of 70 clumps found in the Hi-GAL l=224 field, and already observed with the Mopra telescope, in order to study the ultimate level of fragmentation prior to collapse of an individual fragment into a proto-star. We want to compare the "fragment mass function" (FMF) with the IMF and also want to study its variations as a function of starless and proto-stellar clumps which, in the proposed region appear to be segregated to different filaments. The l=224 field has a well defined distance, it is relatively nearby, and offers the possibility to carry out the proposed analysis with a very good statistical significance. Our simulations show that ALMA+ACA in band 6 offers the best trade-off for both continuum and spectral line observations.
